  "prompt": "Do I need a lawyer prepared NDA when talking to product design & manufacturing consultants? Will a template off the internet work just as well?",
  "response": "While a template can provide a basic framework, it's generally recommended to have a lawyer-prepared NDA, especially when dealing with product design and manufacturing consultants. Here's why:\n\n1. Custom protection\n- Tailored to your specific industry and project\n- Addresses unique aspects of your intellectual property\n- Covers potential scenarios specific to your situation\n\n2. Legal robustness\n- Professionally drafted NDAs are more likely to hold up in court\n- Lawyers understand nuanced legal language\n- Can anticipate potential loopholes in generic templates\n\n3. Comprehensive coverage\n- Covers trade secrets, designs, technical details\n- Defines confidential information precisely\n- Establishes clear consequences for breaches\n\n4. Potential risks with internet templates\n- May be generic or from another jurisdiction\n- Could miss critical protective clauses\n- Might not align with your specific needs\n\n5. Consultant perspective\n- Professional consultants often prefer lawyer-reviewed NDAs\n- Signals seriousness and professionalism\n- Shows you're protecting your interests comprehensively\n\nWhile a template can be a starting point, investing in a lawyer-prepared NDA provides significantly better protection, especially for innovative product designs.\n\nRecommendation: Consult an intellectual property or business lawyer for a tailored NDA.",
